content.description:
Hobson uses an oklch-based color system with CSS custom properties for theming. Styles are items — both kernel styles and user stylesheets.

## oklch Color System

All colors are defined in the oklch color space, which provides perceptually uniform lightness and intuitive hue manipulation:

```css
:root {
  --base-hue: 250;         /* Base hue angle (0-360) */
  --tint-strength: 0.02;   /* How much hue influences grays */
}
```

### Why oklch?

- **Perceptually uniform** — equal steps in lightness look equal to human eyes
- **Intuitive** — hue is an angle, chroma is saturation, lightness is brightness
- **Derivable** — entire palette generated from `--base-hue` and `--tint-strength`
- **Modern** — supported in all modern browsers

## CSS Custom Properties

The theme is defined as CSS custom properties on `:root`:

### Core Variables

```css
:root {
  /* Surface colors (derived from base-hue) */
  --bg-primary: oklch(0.18 var(--tint-strength) var(--base-hue));
  --bg-secondary: oklch(0.22 var(--tint-strength) var(--base-hue));
  --bg-tertiary: oklch(0.26 var(--tint-strength) var(--base-hue));

  /* Text colors */
  --text-primary: oklch(0.90 0.01 var(--base-hue));
  --text-secondary: oklch(0.65 0.01 var(--base-hue));
  --text-muted: oklch(0.50 0.01 var(--base-hue));

  /* Accent colors */
  --accent: oklch(0.65 0.15 var(--base-hue));
  --accent-hover: oklch(0.70 0.17 var(--base-hue));

  /* Borders */
  --border-primary: oklch(0.30 var(--tint-strength) var(--base-hue));
  --border-secondary: oklch(0.25 var(--tint-strength) var(--base-hue));
}
```

### Changing the Theme

Changing `--base-hue` shifts the entire color palette:
- `--base-hue: 250` → blue-tinted dark theme
- `--base-hue: 30` → warm amber theme
- `--base-hue: 150` → green theme

## Style Architecture

### kernel:styles

The [kernel:styles](item://33333333-8888-0000-0000-000000000000) module contains all system CSS. It's a kernel module because styles must load before any rendering happens.

On boot, kernel:styles is injected as a `<style>` element. On hot-reload, only the style element is replaced (no full page reload needed).

### CSS Items

Userland stylesheets are stored as items with CSS code. The `css-loader` library loads them into `<style>` elements on demand.

### Style Scoping

Views can include scoped styles via `<style>` elements in their rendered DOM. These are naturally scoped to the view's DOM subtree when using unique class names.

## Hot-Reload Behavior

When kernel:styles is edited:
- The import system detects it's a styles module
- Only the `<style>` element is replaced
- No full page reload, no re-render needed
- Visual changes appear instantly

